{
  "answer": "Under Massachusetts public records law (Chapter 66, Section 20), agencies must respond to a request for public records within five business days. If additional time is needed, the agency may extend the response deadline by up to ten additional business days, provided it notifies the requester of the extension and the reason for it. This rule applies to records requests directed to the Department of Transitional Assistance, the Executive Office of Health and Human Services, and other agencies that administer Medicaid (MassHealth).",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/doc/chapter-66-public-records-law-2023/pdf",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Massachusetts public records law, agencies must respond to a request for public records, including Medicaid records, within 10 business days of receipt of the request.",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/public-records-law",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Rhode Island law, agencies must respond to public records requests concerning Medicaid within five business days after the request is received, unless an extension is granted for a valid reason.",
  "source": "https://www.ri.gov/records/ (Rhode Island Public Records Law, § 38-2.2)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Rhode Island law requires state agencies, including the Department of Human Services (which processes Medicaid requests), to respond to a public records request within 20 business days of receiving the request.",
  "source": "https://www.ri.gov/records/ (Rhode Island Public Records Act guidelines) and https://dhs.ri.gov/ (Department of Human Services public records policy)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Rhode Island state agencies must respond to public records requests within five (5) business days, as required by the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, and this includes requests for Medicaid records.",
  "source": "https://www.rilegislature.gov/Statutes/Titles/38/38-2-4.HTM",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act, agencies such as the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) must respond to public records requests within 10 calendar days of receipt, unless extensions are granted for clarification or to gather records.",
  "source": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/Pages/FOIA.aspx (California Department of Health Care Services FOIA page)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies must respond to a request for public records, including Medicaid records, within five business days after the request is received, unless an extension is granted by the agency.",
  "source": "https://www.dos.ny.gov/foi/foi.html (New York Department of State, Freedom of Information Law – response time requirements)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), state agencies—including those that handle Medicaid requests—must respond to a public records request within five business days, either by providing the records, denying the request, or stating that additional time is needed.",
  "source": "https://www.dos.ny.gov/openrecords/foillaw.html (New York Department of State, Freedom of Information Law)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies – including the New York State Department of Health and its Medicaid offices – must respond to public records requests within five business days of receipt. If additional time is needed, the agency must provide a written notice of the extension and the reason for it.",
  "source": "https://www.ny.gov/freedom-information-law-foil and https://www.health.ny.gov/about/foi.htm (New York State Department of Health FOIL page)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies, including those that administer Medicaid, must respond to a public records request within five (5) business days after the request is received, unless additional time is needed to locate, review, or exempt the records.",
  "source": "https://www.opr.ny.gov/foi/foi-law",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies must respond to a request for public records – including Medicaid records – within five business days after the request is deemed complete. If the agency needs more time, it must provide a written estimate of the additional time required.",
  "source": "https://www.dhs.ny.gov/openrecords/freedom-of-information-law-foil",
  "confidence": "high"
