{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law (M.G.L. c. 66, § 10), agencies (known as Records Access Officers or RAOs) generally must respond to public records requests within 10 business days of receipt. This applies to records requests directed at MassHealth (Massachusetts Medicaid) as it does to other state agencies. The initial response must either provide the records, identify any records being withheld with reasons, or provide a good-faith estimate of the time and fees required. Extensions may be granted by the Supervisor of Records for up to 20 additional business days (or longer in limited circumstances).",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/public-records-law (M.G.L. c. 66, § 10; 950 CMR 32.00)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law (M.G.L. c. 66, § 10), agencies (known as Records Access Officers) must respond to public records requests within 10 business days of receipt. This applies to requests for Medicaid (MassHealth) records as well. The initial response must either provide the records, indicate when they will be provided, or explain any applicable exemptions. Agencies may request an extension from the Supervisor of Records for more complex requests (up to 25 business days for municipalities and an extended period for state agencies, subject to approval).",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/handbook/a-guide-to-the-massachusetts-public-records-law (Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth, Public Records Division); M.G.L. c. 66, § 10",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law (M.G.L. c. 66, § 10), agencies (records access officers) generally must respond to public records requests within 10 business days of receipt. This applies to records requests made to MassHealth (the Massachusetts Medicaid agency) as well as other state agencies. The initial response must either provide the records, identify them and give a reasonable timeline for production, or explain any denial. If more time is needed, an agency can request an extension from the Supervisor of Records, but any extension generally cannot exceed 25 business days from the initial receipt for state agencies without further approval.",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/public-records-law (Massachusetts Public Records Law, M.G.L. c. 66, § 10); 950 CMR 32.00",
  "confidence": "high"
}

