{
  "answer": "Under the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act (APRA), public agencies generally have 10 business days to respond to a public records request. This deadline can be extended by an additional 20 business days if the agency demonstrates good cause (such as the request being voluminous or requiring legal review). This general APRA timeline applies to Medicaid-related records requests made to the Rhode Island Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS) or the Department of Human Services.",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws § 38-2-3(e) (Access to Public Records Act); http://webserver.rilin.state.ri.us/Statutes/TITLE38/38-2/38-2-3.HTM",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act (APRA), public bodies generally must respond to public records requests within 10 business days. This deadline may be extended by an additional 20 business days if the public body demonstrates that the voluminous nature of the request, the number of requests pending, or the difficulty in searching for and retrieving the records makes compliance within 10 business days impracticable. These timeframes apply to records requests made to Rhode Island state agencies, including those concerning Medicaid records held by the Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS).",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws § 38-2-3(e) (Access to Public Records Act), http://webserver.rilin.state.ri.us/Statutes/TITLE38/38-2/38-2-3.HTM",
  "confidence": "high"
}

