{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (Government Code section 7922.535, formerly section 6253), agencies must determine whether a request seeks disclosable public records and notify the requester of that determination within 10 calendar days of receiving the request. In unusual circumstances, this deadline may be extended by up to 14 additional calendar days with written notice to the requester. Note that the initial 10-day response is a determination of whether records will be produced, not necessarily the production of the records themselves; records must then be produced promptly. This applies to records held by state agencies, including the Department of Health Care Services (which administers Medi-Cal, California's Medicaid program).",
  "source": "California Government Code section 7922.535 (https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?sectionNum=7922.535&lawCode=GOV)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (Government Code § 7922.535, formerly § 6253), agencies must determine whether a request seeks disclosable public records within 10 calendar days of receiving the request and promptly notify the requester of that determination. In unusual circumstances, this deadline may be extended by up to 14 additional days with written notice to the requester. Note that the 10-day period is for the agency's determination, not necessarily for producing the records, which must be provided promptly thereafter. This applies to records requests to agencies administering Medi-Cal (California's Medicaid program), such as the Department of Health Care Services.",
  "source": "California Government Code § 7922.535 (https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?sectionNum=7922.535&lawCode=GOV)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (Government Code § 7922.535, formerly § 6253), state and local agencies generally have 10 calendar days from receipt of a public records request to determine whether the request seeks disclosable public records and to notify the requester of that determination. In 'unusual circumstances,' the agency may extend this deadline by up to 14 additional calendar days with written notice to the requester. This applies to records requests made to agencies administering Medi-Cal (California's Medicaid program), such as the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS). Note that the 10-day period is for the agency's determination, not necessarily for producing the records themselves, which must be provided promptly thereafter.",
  "source": "California Government Code § 7922.535 (https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?sectionNum=7922.535&lawCode=GOV)",
