{
  "answer": "Under New York's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies must respond to public records requests within 5 business days of receiving the request. Within that time, the agency must either grant the request, deny it in writing, or acknowledge receipt of the request in writing and provide an approximate date (generally within 20 business days of the acknowledgment) when the request will be granted or denied. If more than 20 additional business days are needed, the agency must provide a written explanation and a date certain for response. These same FOIL timeframes apply to records requests directed to the New York State Department of Health regarding Medicaid.",
  "source": "New York Public Officers Law § 89(3)(a); NY Committee on Open Government (https://opengovernment.ny.gov/freedom-information-law)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), an agency must respond to a public records request within 5 business days of receipt by either granting access, denying the request in writing, or acknowledging receipt and providing an approximate date (generally within 20 business days) when the request will be granted or denied. If more than 20 business days are needed, the agency must provide a written explanation and a date certain, within a reasonable period under the circumstances, when the request will be granted in whole or in part. This applies to records held by the New York State Department of Health, which administers Medicaid.",
  "source": "https://www.dos.ny.gov/coog/foil2.html (NYS Committee on Open Government) and NY Public Officers Law § 89(3)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

