{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (Chapter 552 of the Texas Government Code), governmental bodies generally must 'promptly' produce public information in response to a request. If the agency believes the requested information may be excepted from disclosure, it must request an Attorney General decision within 10 business days of receiving the request. There is no special, separate deadline for Medicaid-related records; they are subject to the same timeframes, though Medicaid records may be withheld or redacted under confidentiality provisions (such as HIPAA and federal Medicaid confidentiality rules).",
  "source": "Texas Government Code Chapter 552 (Public Information Act), https://statutes.capitol.texas.gov/Docs/GV/htm/GV.552.htm; Texas Attorney General Public Information Handbook, https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/members-public/public-information-act",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (Texas Government Code Chapter 552), governmental bodies, including agencies handling Medicaid records such as the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC), must 'promptly' produce public information in response to a request. If the agency believes the requested information may be withheld or excepted from disclosure, it must request an attorney general's decision within 10 business days of receiving the request. There is no fixed statutory deadline for producing records, but production must be prompt; if information cannot be produced within 10 business days, the agency must certify that fact in writing and set a reasonable date and time for production.",
  "source": "Texas Government Code Chapter 552 (Public Information Act), https://statutes.capitol.texas.gov/Docs/GV/htm/GV.552.htm; Texas Attorney General Public Information Handbook, https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/governmental-bodies/public-information-act",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (Texas Government Code Chapter 552), governmental bodies must 'promptly' produce public information in response to a request. If the requested information is not readily available, the agency must produce it within a reasonable time. If the agency believes the information may be excepted from disclosure, it must request an Attorney General ruling within 10 business days of receiving the request. There is no specific separate timeline for Medicaid-related records; they follow the general Public Information Act timelines administered by the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC).",
  "source": "https://statutes.capitol.texas.gov/Docs/GV/htm/GV.552.htm (Texas Government Code Chapter 552); https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/members-public/how-request-public-information",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (Chapter 552 of the Texas Government Code), a governmental body generally must 'promptly' produce public information in response to a request. If the agency wishes to withhold information and seek an Attorney General ruling, it must request that ruling within 10 business days of receiving the request. If information is not readily available, the agency must certify this and set a date and hour within a reasonable time when the information will be available. These general PIA deadlines apply to Medicaid-related records held by Texas HHSC, though specific records may be confidential under state or federal law (e.g., HIPAA, 42 CFR Part 431 Subpart F).",
  "source": "https://statutes.capitol.texas.gov/Docs/GV/htm/GV.552.htm (Texas Government Code Chapter 552, §§ 552.221 and 552.301)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (Texas Government Code Chapter 552), governmental bodies, including agencies handling Medicaid records such as the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC), must 'promptly' produce public information in response to a request. If the agency believes the requested information is excepted from disclosure, it must request an attorney general's decision within 10 business days of receiving the request. There is no fixed statutory deadline for producing non-exempt records other than 'promptly,' but if information cannot be produced within 10 business days, the agency must certify that fact in writing and set a date and time when it will be available.",
  "source": "Texas Government Code § 552.221 and § 552.301 (https://statutes.capitol.texas.gov/Docs/GV/htm/GV.552.htm); Texas Attorney General's Public Information Act Handbook (https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/governmental-bodies/public-information-act)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

